# Backing Track Research: Comprehensive Findings

---

## Executive Summary

For immediate, free use in a practice app: **WikiLoops** is the single best source (real instruments, filterable by key + BPM + genre, free download). **GuitarToneMaster** is the best dedicated backing track site with full key/BPM filtering. For custom generation, **Suno v5** with a paid plan gives you full key/BPM/genre control and up to 8 minutes — the free plan is non-commercial only and generates shorter tracks with an older model. Udio is comparable but weaker on precise key control.

---

## 1. Suno AI

### Current State (v5, late 2025)
Suno v5 is a significant structural overhaul. The platform now generates up to **8 minutes** of music with professional structural coherence on paid plans. The free Basic plan runs on the older v4.5-All model and has shorter generation limits — the exact free cap isn't publicly posted, but extend/upload features (needed to push past ~2 min) are **paid-only**.

### Specifying Key, BPM, Genre
Suno supports this via inline prompt text in Custom Mode. There is no separate "key" dropdown — you write it directly in the style prompt. Tested patterns that work:

- `instrumental, reggae dub, 80 BPM, A minor, reverb-heavy guitar, offbeat skank, no vocals`
- `desert blues instrumental, E minor, 90 BPM, slide guitar, sparse drums, warm reverb`
- `surf rock instrumental, 120 BPM, A minor, tremolo guitar, reverb, driving drums`

Key specification is honored **approximately** — it gets the tonality right but may not be mathematically locked to A=440 at an exact key. BPM is similarly approximate (usually within ±5 BPM).

### Royalty-Free / License Status
This is the critical catch:

- **Free plan**: Suno retains ownership. You get **non-commercial use only**. Cannot use in an app even for personal distribution.
- **Pro ($8/mo) / Premier ($24/mo)**: You get commercial use rights. You don't own the copyright (AI-generated work isn't copyrightable in the US), but you have a commercial license to distribute and use the tracks.
- For a **personal practice app** shared privately: free plan is technically fine under non-commercial terms.
- For a **deployed/public app**: you need a paid plan.

### Verdict for Your Use Case
Best option for custom tracks matching Gene's DNA exactly (khruangbin-style-80, psych-surf, desert blues). Use the Custom Mode with specific BPM, key, and instrumentation. Pro plan at $8/mo is worth it if you want to generate a library and use them in a deployed app.

---

## 2. Udio AI

### Current State
Udio remains competitive with Suno, with slightly higher audio fidelity noted by reviewers. It focuses heavily on vocal productions but supports full instrumental mode via the Advanced controls panel.

### Specifying Key, BPM, Genre
- **BPM**: Include directly in prompt — `90 BPM`, `slow 70 BPM` works.
- **Key**: Less reliable than Suno. No explicit key parameter. You can write `A minor` or `key of E minor` in the prompt and it will often (not always) comply. Community guides suggest descriptive mood language as backup: `dark minor key` vs. `bright major key`.
- **Genre**: Very prompt-responsive. Handles reggae, afrobeat, bossa nova, surf, psych well.
- **Track length**: Similar constraints — free plan gives 100 monthly / 10 daily credits, each generation = 2 credits, produces ~2 min clips. Paid from $8/mo for longer tracks.

### License Status
Same structure as Suno:
- Free plan: personal/non-commercial only
- Paid plans: commercial rights included

### Verdict for Your Use Case
Udio is a viable alternative to Suno, especially if Suno's key outputs sound off. But Suno v5 is currently ahead in structural coherence and prompt adherence. **Use Suno as primary, Udio as backup for second opinions on a specific vibe.**

---

## 3. Free Backing Track Websites (Ranked for Your Genres)

### Tier 1: Best Options

**WikiLoops** — [wikiloops.com](https://www.wikiloops.com/tracks/track-finder.php)
The clear winner for your use case. Highlights:
- 265,000+ collaboratively recorded tracks (real musicians, not AI)
- **Genres available**: Reggae (2,844 tracks), Blues, BossaNova (4,450+), Funk (21,000+), Soul — afrobeat coverage is thinner
- **Filter by**: Genre, Key (all 12 keys), BPM (adjustable range, e.g., [reggae at 75-76 BPM](https://www.wikiloops.com/tracks/Reggae-75_76bpm.php)), instruments, time signature
- **Download**: Free, licensed under WikiLoops license (free for non-commercial use with attribution; commercial use requires a paid WikiLoops membership ~$6/mo)
- **Specific URLs to bookmark**:
  - Reggae: `wikiloops.com/tracks/Reggae.php`
  - Bossa Nova: `wikiloops.com/tracks/BossaNova.php`
  - Funk: `wikiloops.com/tracks/Funk.php`
  - Key of A minor: `wikiloops.com/tracks/Am.php`

**GuitarToneMaster** — [guitartonemaster.com/guitar-backing-tracks](https://www.guitartonemaster.com/guitar-backing-tracks)
- 3,200+ free backing tracks
- **Genres**: Rock, Blues, Funk, Reggae, Afrobeat (4 tracks), Soul, Groove — no surf or psych label but some crossover
- **Filter by**: Key (all 12 keys), BPM range (42–205 BPM with custom from/to), genre, scale, mood
- **Download**: Mix of free and paid downloads — filter by "Free download" option
- Confirmed: Reggae A minor at 70 BPM tracks exist in catalog

### Tier 2: Solid but More Limited

**YT Jam Tracks** — [ytjamtracks.bandcamp.com](https://ytjamtracks.bandcamp.com/)
- Original backing tracks by creator "Mikee," released free on YouTube
- Genres: Blues, Funk, Soul, R&B, Reggae, Dub
- Confirmed track: "Reggae Dub Backing Track in A Minor" — key always labeled in title
- Free download via Bandcamp (name-your-price, $0 works)
- **Best for**: Dub reggae, soul/funk in specific minor keys

**Karl Golden Music Education** — [karlgolden.org/backing-tracks](https://karlgolden.org/backing-tracks)
- Educator-created, real instruments
- Genres: Rock, Funk, Reggae, Soul, Metal, Lo-Fi
- Key and BPM labeled per track
- Free download

**QuistJam / Quistorama** — [quistorama.com/jamtracks](https://www.quistorama.com/jamtracks)
- YouTube channel + Bandcamp
- Genres: Blues, Jazz-Blues, Reggae-Blues hybrid, Dub
- Key always in track title (e.g., "Reggae Blues Jam Backing Track (Bm)")
- Free on YouTube; Bandcamp pay-what-you-want

### Tier 3: Genre-Specific but Paid or Limited

**JamTracksGuitar** — [jamtracksguitar.com](https://www.jamtracksguitar.com/)
- High quality, real musicians
- Has Reggae (10 tracks), Bossa Nova/Samba (9 tracks), Soul/Funk packs
- **Paid**: $9.90/pack — no key/BPM filter, browse by genre only
- Worth it if you want a professionally curated reggae or bossa nova pack

**Bluesblast** — [bluesblast.com](https://bluesblast.com/)
- Blues, rock, jazz only — no reggae/surf/afrobeat
- Free download, key and tempo labeled in track names
- Useful for desert blues / blues adjacent content

**SOUNDRAW** — [soundraw.io](https://soundraw.io/)
- AI-generated, full key + BPM + genre control (similar to Suno but more structured)
- Free plan: generate and edit in-app but **cannot download** on free tier
- Paid plan required for file export
- Strong for: Lo-fi, funk, soul, afrobeat — weaker for authentic reggae/surf feel

